{
  "core_question": "What analyses must the hospital board conduct across clinical, legal, and financial domains to evaluate a private‑equity acquisition involving nonprofit conversion, sale‑leaseback of real estate, and a charitable foundation holding proceeds?",
  "rationale": "The transaction touches patient care operations (clinical), tax‑exempt status and contractual arrangements (legal), and valuation, financing, and cash‑flow implications (finance).",
  "routes": ["healthcare", "legal", "finance"],
  "sub_questions": {
    "healthcare": "What clinical considerations—including impact on patient care quality, workforce retention, accreditation status, and continuity of services—should the board evaluate when a nonprofit community hospital converts to a for‑profit entity under a private‑equity acquisition?",
    "legal": "From a legal standpoint, what are the key compliance requirements, contractual risks, and regulatory approvals needed for (1) converting the hospital’s nonprofit status to for‑profit, (2) executing a sale‑leaseback of the real estate, and (3) establishing a charitable foundation that holds the proceeds, including IRS 501(c)(3) implications and state licensing considerations?",
    "finance": "What financial analyses—including valuation of the operating entity, lease terms and tax treatment of the sale‑leaseback, projected cash flows, debt capacity, and impact on the hospital’s capital structure—should the board perform to assess the feasibility and value creation potential of this transaction?"
  },
  "requires_recency_disclosure": true,
  "recency_notes": "IRS rules on sale‑leasebacks for hospitals, 501(c)(3) charitable foundation regulations, recent state hospital licensing changes, and current real estate market conditions may have evolved since the specialists’ training cutoff."
}
